<body>
    <div class="container">
        <div class="header">
            <h1>Weber Test Clinical Decision Matrix</h1>
            <p>Comprehensive guide using RIGHT EAR examples for Weber test interpretation</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="quadrant-grid">
            <!-- Quadrant 1: Normal -->
            <div class="quadrant quadrant-1">
                <div class="severity-indicator normal"></div>
                <div class="test-result">Weber: Central (No Lateralization)</div>
                <div class="ear-affected">No Defect</div>
                <div class="loss-type">Normal</div>
                <div class="condition">Normal Hearing</div>
                <div class="interpretation">
                    <strong>Interpretation:</strong> Sound heard equally in both ears. Both ears have similar hearing thresholds. No significant conductive or sensorineural pathology present.
                </div>
                <div class="next-steps">
                    <h4>Next Steps:</h4>
                    <ul class="steps-list">
                        <li>Perform Rinne test to confirm (should be positive bilaterally)</li>
                        <li>Document baseline hearing status</li>
                        <li>Routine follow-up if asymptomatic</li>
                        <li>Consider formal audiometry if patient reports subjective hearing concerns</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <!-- Quadrant 2: Conductive Loss -->
            <div class="quadrant quadrant-2">
                <div class="severity-indicator caution"></div>
                <div class="test-result">Weber: Lateralizes TO Right Ear</div>
                <div class="ear-affected">RIGHT EAR</div>
                <div class="loss-type">CHL</div>
                <div class="condition">RIGHT Conductive Hearing Loss</div>
                <div class="interpretation">
                    <strong>Interpretation:</strong> Sound lateralizes toward the RIGHT ear (affected ear). The right ear has conductive pathology - sound travels better through bone conduction because external noise is blocked by the conductive problem.
                </div>
                <div class="next-steps">
                    <h4>Next Steps:</h4>
                    <ul class="steps-list">
                        <li>Rinne test RIGHT ear (expect NEGATIVE - bone > air)</li>
                        <li>Otoscopic examination of RIGHT ear</li>
                        <li>Look for: earwax, fluid, TM perforation, otitis media</li>
                        <li>Consider tympanometry</li>
                        <li>Audiometry if problem persists</li>
                        <li>ENT referral if no obvious treatable cause</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <!-- Quadrant 3: Sensorineural Loss -->
            <div class="quadrant quadrant-3">
                <div class="severity-indicator urgent"></div>
                <div class="test-result">Weber: Lateralizes AWAY TO Left Ear</div>
                <div class="ear-affected">RIGHT EAR</div>
                <div class="loss-type">SNHL</div>
                <div class="condition">RIGHT Sensorineural Hearing Loss</div>
                <div class="interpretation">
                    <strong>Interpretation:</strong> Sound lateralizes AWAY from the RIGHT ear (toward the better LEFT ear). The RIGHT ear has inner ear, cochlear, or retrocochlear pathology affecting nerve transmission.
                </div>
                <div class="next-steps">
                    <h4>Next Steps:</h4>
                    <ul class="steps-list">
                        <li>Rinne test RIGHT ear (expect POSITIVE - air > bone)</li>
                        <li>**URGENT**: If sudden onset (<72 hours) → immediate oral steroids</li>
                        <li>Formal audiometry</li>
                        <li>MRI brain/IACs if unilateral or progressive</li>
                        <li>Rule out acoustic neuroma/retrocochlear pathology</li>
                        <li>ENT referral (urgent if sudden or progressive)</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <!-- Quadrant 4: Mixed Loss -->
            <div class="quadrant quadrant-4">
                <div class="severity-indicator investigate"></div>
                <div class="test-result">Weber: Variable + Complex Rinne Pattern</div>
                <div class="ear-affected">RIGHT EAR</div>
                <div class="loss-type">Mixed</div>
                <div class="condition">RIGHT Mixed Hearing Loss</div>
                <div class="interpretation">
                    <strong>Interpretation:</strong> RIGHT ear has BOTH conductive AND sensorineural components. Weber lateralization depends on which component dominates. Rinne may be positive or negative depending on severity of conductive component.
                </div>
                <div class="next-steps">
                    <h4>Next Steps:</h4>
                    <ul class="steps-list">
                        <li>Complete Rinne test battery (may be confusing results)</li>
                        <li>Formal audiometry (ESSENTIAL for diagnosis)</li>
                        <li>Comprehensive ENT evaluation</li>
                        <li>Consider CT temporal bones for ossicular pathology</li>
                        <li>May need surgical evaluation</li>
                        <li>Usually treat conductive component first</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="legend-section">
            <div class="legend-title">Medical Terminology Guide</div>
            <div class="legend-grid">
                <div class="legend-category">
                    <h4>Hearing Loss Types</h4>
                    <div class="legend-item">
                        <span class="legend-term">CHL</span>
                        <span class="legend-definition">Conductive Hearing Loss</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="legend-item">
                        <span class="legend-term">SNHL</span>
                        <span class="legend-definition">Sensorineural Hearing Loss</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="legend-item">
                        <span class="legend-term">Mixed</span>
                        <span class="legend-definition">Both CHL + SNHL present</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="legend-item">
                        <span class="legend-term">TM</span>
                        <span class="legend-definition">Tympanic Membrane (eardrum)</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="legend-item">
                        <span class="legend-term">Lateralization</span>
                        <span class="legend-definition">Sound heard more in one ear</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="legend-category">
                    <h4>Clinical Tests & Terms</h4>
                    <div class="legend-item">
                        <span class="legend-term">Tympanometry</span>
                        <span class="legend-definition">Test of eardrum mobility</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="legend-item">
                        <span class="legend-term">Audiometry</span>
                        <span class="legend-definition">Formal hearing test</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="legend-item">
                        <span class="legend-term">IACs</span>
                        <span class="legend-definition">Internal Auditory Canals</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="legend-item">
                        <span class="legend-term">Retrocochlear</span>
                        <span class="legend-definition">Behind the cochlea (nerve/brain)</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="legend-item">
                        <span class="legend-term">Acoustic Neuroma</span>
                        <span class="legend-definition">Benign tumor on hearing nerve</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="priority-legend">
                <div class="priority-item">
                    <span class="legend-dot normal"></span>Routine Care
                </div>
                <div class="priority-item">
                    <span class="legend-dot caution"></span>Needs Investigation
                </div>
                <div class="priority-item">
                    <span class="legend-dot urgent"></span>Urgent Evaluation
                </div>
                <div class="priority-item">
                    <span class="legend-dot investigate"></span>Complex Workup Required
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
